1. Why should we learn Logistic Regression?¶

In a nutshell, logistic regression is a supervised classification technique which,
given a set of examples and their features and class labels,
learns to predict class probabilities for new examples.
From the class probabilities, we can predict class labels for the new examples.

  • Logistic Regression is one of the most widely used machine learning algorithms in the world.
  • Logistic regression is one of the "go to" methods to solve classification problems in Machine Learning; it is a tool that should be in every data scientists tool box.

2. Binary classification with continuous feature(s)¶

Many problems in the real world involve predicting a binary outcome ($0$ or $1$) as a function of some independent continuous variables that we believe may be associated with the outcome. F

For example we could observe whether or not a group of individuals has Diabetes ($0$ or $1$), and collect numerical data such as blood presssure, glucose level, body mass index, age, etc. from each individual in the group. We could then build a model to try to predict whether a person has diabetes or not, given their data for this set of features.

In Section S.3 of the Supplementary Material below, we present a Case Study along these lines, in which we analyze the Pima Indians Diabetes Data Set

In this section we develop an approach to binary classification problems with continuous features.

Suppose we have a sample of data points, each with a vector of features $x$ and a binary label $y$

We start with the notion that there is a signal $z$ which is linear in the feature(s), and which may help predict the outcome:

$z = w^{T}x + b$, where

  • $x$ is a column vector of features (real numbers),
  • $w$ is a column vector of associated weights (real numbers),
  • $w^{T}$ is the transpose of $w$, so it's a row vector, and
  • $b$ is a constant bias (a real number).

The problem of classification can be broken down as follows:

  • Find a model, i.e. a way to compute the outcome as a function of the features, given a hypothesis $(w,b)$ and a data point $x$
  • Identify the best hypothesis $(w,b)$ i.e. the particular $w$ and $b$ that gives the best predictions for the outcomes.

Question
Given a vector of feature values $x$, the associated vector of weights $w$ and the bias $b$:
Is the signal $z=w^{T}x + b$ a vector or a scalar?

In Section 3 we present a Case Study in which we first develop a simple toy binary classification problem, and then solve it by two different methods:

  • Linear Regression (which should already be familiar)
  • Logistic Regression

In the process, we'll introduce Logistice Regression and explain how it is used in classification problems. You will see how Linear and Logistic Regression differ, and what makes Logistic Regression a better tool for binary classification problems.

3. Case Study: MNIST digit classification in one dimension¶

The MNIST data set is a set of $70,000$ grayscale images of the digits $0$ through $9$, with roughly equal numbers of examples of each digit.
The images are $28$x$28$ pixels, so each image has $28^2=784$ pixels, which can be considered as the features
In a grayscale image, the pixels each have values ranging from $0$ to $255$, where $0$ is darkest, and $255$ is brightest
The pixels defining the digit are bright, while background pixels are dark.

We'll separate the MNIST images into two classes:

  • class $1$: the digit is a $1$, and
  • class $0$: digit is not a $1$

Digits with shorter "lengths" have fewer bright pixels, so we expect their images to have lower mean pixel values than images of digits with longer "lengths".

The $1$ generally has the shortest "length" of all the digits, and thus the fewest bright pixels

So we expect images of the digit $1$ to have lower average pixel value than images of all other digits

By representing each image by itsaverage pixel value, we reduce the $784$ dimensional set of features to one dimension. This is an example of feature engineering. In this case we created the new feature because we expect it to help separate the two classes.

Next, we'll test out the idea: we'll build a classifier that predicts whether or not an image is a $1$, given only its average pixel value.

Question Looking at the histogram below, can you think of other useful ways that we could have reduced the image to a single number?

In [22]:
# Correct for class imbalance by downsampling, 
#     so that there are equal numbers of examples in classes '1' and 'not 1'
# Set labels to 1 for class '1' and to zero for class 'not 1'
inds_not_1 = random.sample(range(len(y[y!='1'])), len(y[y=='1']))
y_not_1 = y[y!='1'][inds_not_1]
y_not_1 = np.array(['0' for x in range(len(y_not_1))])
X_not_1 = X[y!='1'][inds_not_1]
X_1 = X[y=='1']
y_1 = y[y=='1']
y = np.concatenate((y_1,y_not_1),axis=0)
# reverse direction of X so that logistic curve bends upward to the right
X = -np.concatenate((X_1,X_not_1),axis=0)
print(X.shape,y.shape)

(15754,) (15754,)

3.2 Build a classifier with ordinary least squares regression¶

One approach would be to fit the signal $z$ directly to the label values 0 and 1, via least squares.

We can make predictions with our least squares model by applying a threshold of $0.5$ and predicting the positive class for all data points with $z > 0.5$ and the negative class for all data points with $z \le 0.5$.

So yes, we can use least squares regression to solve binary classification problems, but as we'll see later, it's not optimal.

3.3 Logistic regression: a probability-based approach to classification¶

What if we regard each outcome (zero or one) as a noisy, rounded-off estimate of the class probability, .i.e. the probability of being in the positive class?
I.e. if the class probability of an example is $\le \frac{1}{2}$, it would round off to 0, and the example would be in class $0$
And if the class probability of an example is $> \frac{1}{2}$, it would round it off to 1, and the example would be in class $1$

We observe only the feature(s) and outcomes of the examples in the training set, and we want to solve for the underlying class probability distribution that is consistent with the observed outcomes.

Quick Exercise: "Logistic Regression by hand
Looking at a graph showing the outcomes vs. the feature, can you draw a curve that fits the data better than the regression line, and looks like probabilities? Take a few minutes to try.
Congratulations, you have just done a qualitative version of logistic regression on the data!

Can we find a way to map the signal $z$ directly to the class probabilities?

The logistic function¶

It turns out that there is a special function that can do just the sort of mapping that we have in mind!
It's called the logistic (or sigmoid) function:

Given a signal $z$ ranging over the real numbers in $[-\infty,+\infty]$

$\sigma(z) = \frac{1}{1+e^{-z}}$

$\sigma$ maps the real numbers onto the the interval $[0,1]$, thus turning them into probabilities!

Questions

  • What happens to $e^{-z}$ as z goes to $-\infty$?
  • What happens to $e^{-z}$ as z goes to $+\infty?$
  • What happens to $e^{-z}$ as z goes to $0$?

Do the following computations by hand:

  • $\sigma(-\infty)=$?
  • $\sigma(+\infty)=$?
  • $\sigma(0)=$?

plt.grid()
plt.legend(loc=2, prop={'size': 18});

Logistic regression¶

Logistic regression begins with the assumption that there is a linear signal $z = w^{T}x + b$ in the data
that can be mapped to a probability via the logistic function.

$prob(y=1|z) = \sigma(z) = \frac{1}{1+e^{-z}} = \frac{1}{1+exp(-w^{T}x - b)}$

Here, the symbol $|$ is interpreted as "given".

The notation $prob(y=1|z)$ denotes the class probability, which is the probability that the outcome is the positive class given $z$.

The logistic regression approach to classification:
Given observations of the feature(s) and the $0$ or $1$ outcomes, we want to find a hypothesis (values of the weights $w$ and the bias $b$) that generates class probabilities that are as close as possible to the observed distribution of outcomes.

This is a nonlinear problem which, unlike linear regression, has no closed form solution.
In the Supplement section, we will develop and implement a powerful and effective method for solving problems of this kind.

For now, we'll use scikit-learn's LogisticRegression to obtain the solution.
Evidently, the logistic regression model more closely resembles the outcome distribution than does the linear regression line.
A key advantage of logistic regression is that it gives class probabilities for each example, which measure our confidence in each classification.

4. Wrap-up and Summary¶

We solved the MNIST classification problem with both linear regression and logistic regression.
In general, logistic regression is better for classification, though in this case we got a slightly better result with linear regression.

The reasons are

  • Logistic regression is more interpretable since it gives class probabilities
  • Logistic regression is less sensitive to imbalanced data
  • Logistic regression is easily extended to multiple class problems
  • On the other hand, Linear regression cannot generally be used for problems with more than two classes.

In this lesson we learned two approaches to solve a simple 1-dimensional binary classification problem with the MNIST data set

  • Linear Regression
  • Logistic Regression

We also learned

  • The logistic function and how to compute it
  • An advantage of using Logistic Regression over Linear Regression is that it yields class probabilities for its predictions
  • How to use the sklearn library to solve simple binary classification problems

Appendix¶

A.1 The variety of classification problems

Classes can be

  • binomial (2 classes)
  • multinomial (K classes, with K > 2)
  • ordinal (K > 2 classes, with ordered class values, such as Good, Better, Best)

Predictors (features) can be

  • discrete (also called categorical)
  • continuous
  • a mix of discrete and continuous

Class labels can be

  • single: each example has only one class label, as in has heart disease and doesn't have heart disease
  • multiple: each example may have more than one class label, as a scene in a satellite image can contain farmland, a residential area, a river, and/or clouds.

Examples of classification problems that can be addressed with logistic regression

  • Image Data: lung cancer detection
  • Text Data: sentiment classification of movie reviews
  • Tabular Data:
    -- Predict the probability that a person will have a heart attack given blood pressure, age, weight
    -- Fraud detection in bank transaction data
    -- Predict the quality of a wine from physico-chemical measurements

B. A multi-class, multiple label problem
C. A multi-class problem with ordinal labels

In this lesson we'll focus on binary (two-class) classification problems with continuous features¶

A2. Assumptions of Logistic Regression¶

  • there two distinct classes, and each example belongs to exactly one of these classes
  • examples are independent
  • features are not too highly correlated with each other
  • the decision boundary is linear, i.e. the signal that is used to separate the classes is linear in the features
  • the sample size is large relative to the number of features
  • there are no outliers in the data

A3. Strengths and weaknesses of Logistic Regression¶

Advantages:¶

  • yields class probabilities as well as class predictions
  • easy to implement
  • training and inference are fast
  • the model is interpretable because the coefficients (weights) directly measure the feature importances
  • can be extended to multi-class, or multi-label problems

Disadvantages¶

  • assumes that the relevant signal that separates the classes is linear in the features
  • cannot handle nonlinear problems where the functional form of the signal is unknown
  • tends to overfit in high-dimensional data sets

  2. Understand and be able to explain the method of maximum likelihood, and its role in logistic regression
  3. Understand and be able to explain how gradient descent works, in a qualitative way

S.1 Theory: The Mathematics of Logistic Regression¶

S.1.1 The Maximum Likelihood Method¶

The maximum likelihood method offers a way to carry out the logistic regression approach.
We compute the "likelihood" of the observed data, given a hypothesis (weights and bias).
We then find the hypothesis -- specific values $(w,b)$ -- that maximizes the likelihood of observing the data that we got.

Sounds reasonable, right?
But you might raise a number of questions:

  • What do we mean by the "likelihood"?
  • How can we compute the "likelihood"?
  • How can we maximize the "likelihood"?

Likelihood of a data point¶

Suppose we observe a data point, an outcome $y$ that is either $0$ or $1$, along with its associated feature $x$
As we have seen, given a hypothesis $(w,b)$ we can predicts the positive class probability $p$ for this data point

We define the likelihood of this data point (given the hypothesis) as the positive class probability, which we can write as

$L \equiv p^{y}(1-p)^{1-y}$
Keep in mind that, although for simplicity it is not explicitly shown, both $p$ and $L$ are functions of the data and the hypothesis:
$p = p(x,w,b)$ and $L = L(x,w,b)$

Exercise
Suppose a hypothesis predicts a positive class probability of $p=0.7$ for a data point.

Compute the likelihood $L$ of the data point for each possible outcome:

  • $y=1$, then $L = $ ?
  • $y=0$, then $L = $ ?

If we observe an outcome of $y=1$ and our model predicts a positive class probability of $0.7$, then the hypothesis is relatively good, since it is consistent with the observed data
On the other hand, if the model had predicted a positive class probability of $0.3$ then we'd say the hypothesis is bad, because it's inconsistent with the observed data.

The likelihood function¶

The likelihood function $\mathcal{L}(X,w,b)$ is defined to be the likelihood of the whole data set. How can we compute $\mathcal{L}$?
Remember that we defined the likelihood of an individual data point as the probability that the outcome is the positive class. Since the data points are assumed to be independent, the likelihood function is just the product of the likelihoods of the individual data points:

$\mathcal{L}(X,w,b) \equiv \Pi_{i=1}^{m} L_{i} = \Pi_{i=1}^{m} p_{i}^{y_{i}}(1-p_{i})^{1-y_{i}}$ where $m$ is the number of data points.

Again, keep in mind that $p$ is a function of the data and the hypothesis: $p = p(x,w,b)$

Question
Is the likelihood function a vector or a scalar?

In a nutshell, the maximum likelihood method seeks to find the hypothesis that is most consistent with the data, i.e. the $(w,b)$ that maximizes the likelihood function $\mathcal{L}(X,w,b)$.

We note that maximizing the likelihood is the same as maximizing the log-likelihood, which simplifies the product into a sum

$log(\mathcal{L}(w,b)) = \sum_{i=1}^{m} (y_{i}log(p_{i}) + (1-y_{i})log(1-p_{i}))$

So log-likelihood is a quantitative measures of how much we should trust our hypothesis. The higher the log-likelilhood, the more consistent the data is with the hypothesis and therefore more believable is the hypothesis.

S.1.2 The cross-entropy loss function¶

Maximizing the log-likelihood function is equivalent to minimizing the cross-entropy loss function $\mathcal{J}(w,b)$, defined as

$\mathcal{J}(w,b) \equiv -\frac{1}{m}\sum_{i=1}^{m} (y_{i}log(p_{i}) + (1-y_{i})log(1-p_{i}))$

Questions

  • Can $y_{i}log(p_{i})$ or $(1-y_{i})log(1-p_{i})$ ever be negative?
  • What is the value of the term $y_{i}log(p_{i}) + (1-y_{i})log(1-p_{i})$ in the cross-entropy function for a data point $i$ whose predicted probability $p_{i}$ exactly matches the outcome $y_{i}$? Hint: separately consider the possible outcomes $y_{i}=1$ and $y{i}=0$

The cross-entropy loss function is a measure of the error between the predicted probability distribution of the outcomes matches the actual distribution of the outcomes. Values significantly less than $1$ are are generally good.

So far so good. We have a way to measure the error in our predictions -- the cross-entropy loss. Just as we did for least squares regression, we know what to do next: find the parameters that minimize the error! In other words, we have to find the hypothesis $(w,b)$ that minimizes the cross-entropy loss.

So we know where we're going. But how do we get there?
Next we will see that the Method of Gradient Descent can offer us a prescription for how to "get to the bottom of things"!

S.1.3 The Method of Gradient Descent¶

In a nutshell: the Method of Gradient Descent says that to find the minimum of a function you start with random values of the parameters -- in our case, the weights $w$ and the bias $b$ -- and then iteratively adjust the parameters so as to take small steps in the "downhill" direction, until you reach the lowest point.

But how should we adjust the parameters? It turns out that the adjustment to a parameter should be proportional to the negative partial derivative of the loss function with respect to that parameter. This can be shown using calculus, but is beyond the scope of this lesson, so we'll have to accept it on faith.

So here is the prescription for the "Method of Gradient Descent":

Repeat until convergence: {

$w_{j} \leftarrow w_{j} - \alpha \frac{\partial \mathcal{J}(w,b)}{\partial w_{j}}$
$b \leftarrow b - \alpha \frac{\partial \mathcal{J}(w,b)}{\partial b}$
where $\alpha$ is a positive constant called the learning rate.

}

In the next section we will build a Logistic Regression Solver that implements the Method of Gradient Descent to minimize the cross-entropy loss function. From the resulting $(w,b)$ we can then compute the positive class probability distribution that is closest to the distribution of outcomes found in the data.

S.2 Implementation: build a logistic regression classifier from scratch¶

In this section we'll use a "divide and conquer" strategy to build the logistic regression model from its essential pieces:

  • The main function logistic_regression implements logistic regression via gradient descent

The required helper functions are

  • logistic computes the logistic function
  • cross_entropy computes the cross entropy loss function
  • grad_loss computes the gradient of the loss function with respect to the weights and bias
  • predict_y predicts class probabilities and labels for new examples
In [51]:
def cross_entropy(y, y_proba):
    '''
     Compute the cross-entropy loss function, which is appropriate for binary classification problems
     Inputs: 
        y: column vector with true label (1 or 0) for each example
        y_proba: column vector with predicted probability of class 1 for each example
     Output: 
        cross_entropy loss: scalar, mean of NLL over all examples
        negative_log_loss is negative log likelihood for each example
    '''
    
    # compute negative log loss (cross-entropy loss)
    negative_log_loss = -(y*np.log(y_proba) + (1. - y)*np.log(1. - y_proba))
    return np.mean(negative_log_loss)
In [52]:
def logistic(z):
    '''
    Compute the logistic function
    Input: 
       z: a vector of real numbers
    Output: 
       y_proba: logistic function of z: a vector of probabilities, real numbers on the interval [0,1]
    '''
    
    # constants
    eps = 1.e-15
    
    # logistic function
    y_proba = 1./(1. + np.exp(-z))
    
    # Fix y_proba overflow/underflow problem
    y_proba[y_proba >= 1.] = 1. - eps
    y_proba[y_proba <= 0.] = eps
    return y_proba
In [53]:
def predict_y(X, w, b):
    '''
    Predict the probability of the positive class, 
    based on a hypothesis (w,b) for a matrix X of input examples 
    Inputs:
       X: input data matrix -- 1 column of feature values for each example
       w: weights -- column vector, length = number of features
       b: bias, a scalar
     Outputs:
       y_proba: a column vector, length = number of examples
    '''
    
    # constants
    max_log = 40.
    
    # Compute z, a row vector with length = number of examples
    z = w.T@X + b
    # Fix the z overflow/underflow problem
    z[z>max_log] = max_log
    z[z<-max_log] = -max_log
    
    # predicted probability of the positive class
    y_proba = logistic(z).T
    return y_proba
In [54]:
def grad_loss(X, y, w, b):
    '''
    Compute the gradient of the loss function for logistic regression
    Inputs:
       X -- input data array, with a column of feature values for each example
       y -- labels, column vector with length = number of examples 
       w -- weights, column vector with length = number of features
       b -- bias, scalar
     Outputs:
       gradient -- dictionary with keys 'dw' and 'db'
          gradient['dw'] -- column vector of partial derivatives of loss function w.r.t. weights,
             length = number of features
          gradient['db'] -- scalar partial derivative of loss function with respect to bias
    ''' 
    
    # constants
    n_examples = len(y)
    
    # predict probability of positive class, based on hypothesis (w ,b)
    y_proba = predict_y(X,w,b)
    
    # partial derivatives of the loss function w.r.t. bias and weight parameters
    db = np.mean(y_proba - y)
    dw = X@(y_proba - y)/n_examples
    
    # put the gradients in a dictionary
    gradient = {'dw':dw, 'db':db }
    return gradient
In [55]:
def logistic_regression(X, y, loss_function=cross_entropy, learning_rate=1.e-3,
                     max_iter=100, tol=1.e-4, verbose=False):
    '''
    Fit a logistic regression model to a set of inputs X with their labels y
    Inputs:
       X -- input data matrix -- 1 column for each example
       y -- labels, column vector with length = number of examples 
     Outputs:
       parameters -- dictionary with keys 'weights' and 'bias'
          parameters['weights'], column vector of weights with length = number of features
          parameters['bias'], scalar
       losses -- column vector of losses on each iteration
    '''
    
    # constants
    n_features = np.size(X,axis=0)

    # initialize
    np.random.seed(42)
    iter_count = 0    
    # Randomly initialize weights from a uniform distribution and initialize the bias to zero
    b = 0.
    w = np.random.uniform(-1,1,(n_features,1))
    losses = np.zeros((max_iter,1))
    delta_w = np.ones((n_features,1))
    delta_b = 1.
    
    # Gradient descent step: update the weights and bias
    # Termination is controlled by the parameters max_iter and tol, 
    #     and occurs when the iteration count reaches max_iter,
    #     or when the weight and bias updates are all below a specified threshold
    while iter_count < max_iter and not( abs(delta_b) < tol  and  (abs(delta_w) < tol).all() ):
        
        # Compute weight and bias parameter updates, via backpropagation
        gradient = grad_loss(X,y,w,b)
        delta_w = -learning_rate*gradient['dw']
        delta_b = -learning_rate*gradient['db']
        if(verbose):
            print(f'iter# {iter_count} delta_b {delta_b:.4f} mean(abs(delta_w)) {np.mean(abs(delta_w)):.4f}')

        # update parameters
        w += delta_w
        b += delta_b
        
        # predict probability of positive class, based on new hypothesis (w,b)
        y_proba = predict_y(X,w,b)
        
        # compute cross-entropy loss for the current iteration
        losses[iter_count] = loss_function(y, y_proba)
        
        # increment iterations counter
        iter_count += 1
            
    # Predict the class
    thresh = 0.5
    y_pred = y_proba > thresh
    
    # Put parameters in a dictionary
    parameters={'weights':w, 'bias':b}

    return parameters, losses[:iter_count], y_proba, y_pred

S.3 Case study: Pima Indians diabetes data set¶

This data set consists of eight features (see list below) for each of 768 female Pima Indians, along with whether or not they have diabetes.

We will use our logistic regression code to build a classification model that, given the values of these features for a female Pima Indian, can accurately predict whether or not she has diabetes.

The data set is publicly available at https://data.world/uci/pima-indians-diabetes Attribute Information (columns)

  1. Number of times pregnant
  2. Plasma glucose concentration at 2 hours in an oral glucose tolerance test
  3. Diastolic blood pressure (mm Hg)
  4. Triceps skin fold thickness (mm)
  5. 2-Hour serum insulin (mu U/ml)
  6. Body mass index (weight in kg/(height in m)^2)
  7. Diabetes pedigree function (I believe this has to do with whether parents or ancestors had diabetes)
  8. Age (years)
  9. Class variable (0 = dose not have diabetes, 1 = has diabetes)

Correlation matrix¶

Shows the degree of independence of the features. Correlation ranges between -1 and 1; a value of

  • 0 means the features are uncorrelated.
  • 1 means the features are perfectly correlated
  • -1 means the features are anti-correlated i.e. one feature is proportional to the negative of the other

Note that the correlation matrix is symmetric about the diagonal, since the order in a correlated pair doesn't matter. Logistic regression assumes all features are uncorrelated, so low correlation is good, and features with high correlation could be problematic.

Three feature pairs stand out as having relatively high (> 0.35) correlation:

  • (pregnant, age)
  • (skin, insulin)
  • (skin, bmi)

Question: can you explain why any of these feature pairs might be correlated?

Also, the class label is correlated with the glucose reading (label,glucose), indicating that glucose will be a powerful predictor in our model.

The ROC curve¶

ROC is the abbreviation for Receiver Operating Characteristic. The ROC curve is a plot of True positive Rate (TPR) as a function of False Positive Rate (FPR). It shows a model's detection capability as a function of decision threshold (FPR is a proxy for decision threshold).

If you set the decision threshold at zero (classify everything as positive), then the true positive rate (TPR) is $1$, since all the positives are correctly classified, and the FPR is also $1$ (since all the negative examples are misclassified as positives!). This is the top right of the ROC curve at $(1,1)$

On the other hand, if you set the decision threshold at 1, then no positive class is detected (no probability can be greater than 1), so the TPR is zero and the FPR is also zero (no positives were misclassified!). This is the point at the bottom left of the ROC curve, at $(0,0)$

The AUC metric¶

A classifier's AUC metric is the area under the ROC curve. Its advantage is that it is independent of class imbalance.
Formally, the AUC metric measures the probability that the model will rank a randomly chosen positive example higher than a randomly chosen negative example. In other words, the AUC metric gives the probability that the model will correctly classify a random pair of opposite-class examples.

For a perfect classifier, the ROC curve is a horizontal line at TPR = 1, and has AUC = 1

The worst possible classifier is based on random chance (i.e., classify each example by flipping a coin); the ROC curve is a diagonal line from (0,0) to (1,1) and has AUC of 0.50.

For a good classifier, the ROC curve bulges above the diagonal toward the line at TPR = 1, and the AUC is significantly higher than 0.5
